In article <2o3u1o$2fh@gza-client1.aktis.com>,
Donald T. Davis <don@cam.ov.com> wrote:
>>Juha Nurmi, tel. (931)2407379 (jnurmi@tnclus.tele.nokia.fi) wrote:
>>: Could someone please tell me what's the correct English term for the 
>>: phenomenon that secret encryption keys gradually "get old" and their
>>: risk to be revealed increases if not changed often enough?
>>
>>: Thanks in advance,
>>
>>: Juha Nurmi
>>: Nokia Telecommunications, Finland
>
>i believe shannon's term, "unicity distance," applies here;
>it is the smallest amount of ciphertext needed to uniquely
>determine the key. otherwise, i suppose you could say that
>the probability that a key has not been compromised, decays
>exponentially with time.			-don davis. openvision
>
>

Um, I think the term Juha is looking for is "aging".  As in key aging
and password aging.  I seem to recall this term from Denning's book
(but don't hold me to that - I seem to be "aging" a little myself and
the memory isn't real clear on the point :)


--Dane

